SENATE RESOLUTION NO. 159
BY SENATOR CLOUD
A RESOLUTION
To create and provide for the Child Permanency Task Force to study and make
recommendations to improve child safety and well-being and achieve timely
permanency outcomes for children in foster care.
WHEREAS, critical timeframes begin the moment that a child is taken into the
custody of the state and placed in foster care as a result of being unsafe due to abuse or
neglect; and
WHEREAS, timely and informed judicial decision-making in child welfare
proceedings is essential to ensuring the ongoing safety and well-being of children in foster
care; and
WHEREAS, each step in a foster care court proceeding has the potential to increase
or decrease time for reunification, adoption, guardianship, or custody and thereby has a
direct impact on achieving "permanency"; and
WHEREAS, a child's stay in foster care ends when permanency is achieved and
expedited permanency prevents children from lingering in the foster care system; and
WHEREAS, federal and state law, including the Louisiana Children's Code, requires
proceedings to be conducted expeditiously to avoid delays in achieving permanency for
children; and
WHEREAS, Louisiana adopted the Administration for Children and Families' (ACF)
"A Home for Every Child Initiative", which focuses on improving the foster care system for
children and families by creating a faster and more efficient pathway to permanency; and
WHEREAS, the Adoption and Safe Families Act of 1997 (ASFA) laid the foundation
for establishing permanency as one of three critical child welfare system goals because
permanency and child safety are crucial for achieving a child's well-being; and
WHEREAS, a complex structure of laws, judicial rules, policies, procedures,
processes, and practices in Louisiana affect timelines to achieving permanency; and
WHEREAS, a comprehensive approach will achieve timely permanency for children
