THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the Senate of the Legislature of Louisiana
does hereby create the Child Permanency Task Force to study and make recommendations
to improve child safety and well-being and achieve timely permanency outcomes for
children in foster care, and to evaluate, report, and propose recommendations for legislation,
court rule changes, professional training enhancements, and reforms to agency policy and
practice.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the task force shall focus on guiding principles,
which include, at a minimum, consideration of the following:
(1) Procedural barriers to permanency.
(2) Appropriate balance, consistent with federal and state law, between the due
process rights of the parents and the need of the child for permanency when reunification is
not readily available.
(3) Meaningful opportunity for foster caregivers to be heard at all stages of the
proceeding, including in-court participation.
(4) Statutory and procedural timelines for child in need of care and termination of
parental rights proceedings and appeals, including but not limited to trial court return dates,
lodging of the appellate record, appellate procedure deadlines, issuance of judgments, and
time delays for seeking supervisory or discretionary review.
(5) Continuances in child in need of care cases and termination of parental rights
proceedings.
(6) Implementation of continuous quality improvement best practices.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Child Permanency Task Force shall be
comprised of one representative, with expertise in the Louisiana Children's Code and other
relevant laws, court rules, and policies, appointed by each of the following organizations:
(1) Louisiana Supreme Court.
(2) Louisiana Conference of Court of Appeal Judges.
(3) Louisiana Clerks of Court Association.
(4) Louisiana Court Administrators Association.
(5) Louisiana Court Reporters Association.
